Models of Addiction: Relevance for Minorities
By Julia Nelson Hagemaster, Ph.D., R.N.

Problems associated with drug use have been rated in recent years as one of this country’s most pressing. The seriousness of the drug crisis motivated both the President’s signing of the Omnibus Anti-Drug Abuse Act for a drug-free generation and the forming of Media-Advertising Partnership for a
’ Drug-Free America by many of the nation’s largest
business corporations. The problems that we are experiencing are not surprising when one considers society’s emphasis on individualism, the widening gap between socioeconomic levels, and the stressors encountered in the workplace and at home.2
Trends in Alcohol and Other Drug Use
Alcohol is by far the most commonly used drug in the United States.3 This is probably because it is legal (for those of certain ages), readily available, inexpensive, and socially acceptable. A recent survey conducted by the National Institute of Drug Abuse4 reveals that levels of consumption differ among four distinct age groups: (1) youth (12-17); (2) young adults (18-25); middle adults (26-34); and older adults (35+).4Young adults represent the largest percentage of heavy drinkers, that is, those who have had 5 or more drinks on one occasion on 5 or more occasions in the past month. Older adults include the smallest proportion of heavy drinkers. While there is a noted increase in abstention among men aged 28-32, there is also evidence of increased numbers of heavy drinkers and drinkers among young people in their twenties. Men are more likely than women to be drinkers and to be heavy drinkers. Although perceptions that drinking patterns of men and women are converging, there is no empirical evidence to support the assertion.’
Because psychoactive drugs such as cocaine and heroin are not legal, information related to patterns of use is not readily available from public sources and estimates have to be made based on self-report surveys.s One such survey conducted by NIDA4 maintains that 37% of all Americans aged 12 and older have used illicit drugs one or more times in

their lives. In addition, 85% have used alcohol and 75% have used cigarettes. Marijuana is the most commonly used illicit drug followed by cocaine and nonmedically used sedatives, tranquilizers, stimulants, and analgesics.‘
Models of Addiction
The root cause of alcoholism and other drug addictions remains a subject of much controversy. Theories of abuse are usually categorized into various models that reflect either a biological determinant of disease or psychological disorder. Some of the more commonly recognized models of addiction include: ( I ) the Medical Model; (2) Behavior Modification Model; (3) Psychological Model; and (4) Social Model.
The Medical Model The medical model, or disease model of alcoholism was first described by Jellinek in 1960.7 He characterized a progressive, downward spiral of symptoms and behavior distinguishing four phases of alcoholism: (1) the prealcoholic stage differentiated by the development of tolerance; (2) early alcoholism; (3) frank addiction; and (4) chronic illness. The latter thre’eaddictive stages are marked by physical dependency and a loss of control. Jellinek developed the Progressive Stage Theory within a medical framework, depicting alcoholism as a disease with more than 40 specific symptoms. Of great importance is the issue of control that is seen as the link in progression from symptomatic to addictive drinking.
The medical model is based on a concept which recognizes the physician as the primary therapist and emphasizes the use of tranquilizers and medications such as disulfiram (Antabuse). Biological variables are stressed with little attention given to psychological and/or social problems. During the past 15 years, research has revealed physiological predispositions in the development of diseases of a d d i ~ t i o n A. ~n individual’s metabolism of alcohol and the toxic effects on body organs, for example, appear to be

