directly related to the interaction of a number of different genes.
In accordance with the biological perspective, many studies have been done with a focus on the family, twins, and adoption. Family studies reveal a 3-4 times increased risk for alcoholism in sons and daughters of alcoholics; twin research indicates a twofold greater risk for alcoholism in identical twins; and adoption studies where the children of alcoholics were raised by someone other than the biological parents reveal a 3-4 times greater risk of becoming alcoholics themselves.
Begleiter et al. ’s9 research findings demonstrate that 80% of the alcoholics he tested with the Evoked Brain Potential had abnormal brain waves despite their number of months of sobriety. The P3 wave associated with emotion and memory was either absent or lower than normal. The test was then given to 25 boys, aged 7-1 3,who were sons of alcoholics but who had not yet been exposed to alcohol themselves. Abnormally flat P3 waves were found in 35% of the sample, along with slight problems with memory and emotional response. This is consistent with findings from studies which show children of alcoholics have an increased risk for alcoholism.
Unique patterns in blood proteins have been observed in alcoholics regardless of length of abstinence. These include a major enzyme of ethanol degradation, at least four isoenzymes important in the metabolism of brain neurotransmitters,and some blood antigens.’ It is important to note that the aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH) isoenzyme in the liver varies greatly among different ethnic groups. For example, it is missing in 30-50% of Orientals, resulting in a syndrome of facial flushing, palpitations, and nausea that resembles a disulfiram (Antabuse) interaction.
Behavior Modification Models Behavior modification models emphasize conditioning principles in understanding the development of addiction. Treatment includes behavior modification therapy, aversive conditioning, and positive reinforcement. lo Pavlovian conditioning that relates unpleasant events (i.e. , electric shock, nausea, etc.) with the sight, smell, and/or taste of alcohol is the premise of aversion therapy. Studies reveal that this approach is not very effective and seems to work only with patients who have a good prognosis anyway, that is, those who are married, employed, and highly motivated.
’ A behavioral approach that involves teaching cop-
ing skills is more widely used. These skills include recognizing peer pressure and learning ways to han-

