dle it. Attention is also given to high-risk situations and alternative behaviors that can be used. For example, if an individual is accustomed to having a drink before dinner, a nonalcoholic drink could be substituted and the time gap before dinner could be shortened by adjusting mealtime.
Much controversy surrounds the behavior-management approach to “controlled” drinking. This involves teaching methods to limit alcohol intake by using such strategies as drinks with lower alcohol content and keeping track of each drink. Some research studies have reported positive results from this treatment approach, others have not.
The Psychological Model Early psychological theories on addiction were based on Freud’s ideas of individual pursuit of euphoric relief from depression through use of substances as substitutes for gratifying oral and genital needs.7 Later views of addiction stressed the role of substance abuse as a balance between regression to psychosis and the development of ego coping mechanisms. Psychological models now include aspects of an alcoholic, or addictive, personality and place emphasis on subconscious conflict. Important to the concept are the individual’s level of maturity, inadequacies of personal and social relatedness, and willingness to face
’ reality . Levin’ maintains that alcoholics suffer from a developmental inability to love themselves that results in a state of “archaic self.” A state of psychological distress known as pathological narcissism results that is relieved only by the use of drugs. Treatment addresses replacing self-esteem through a therapist assisted inquiry into the self, participation in a self-help group like Alcoholics Anonymous, and patient education.
Sullivan and HaleI2 posit that most nurses believe alcoholism has a psychological basis. Their study reveals that nurses who believe in a physical-genetic etiology recommend a medical model form of treatment, while those who view the disease in terms of moral weakness advocate social rejection. It becomes disturbingly clear that the nurse’s attitude in caring for the AODA client can influence the success of a treatment program.
The Social Model The importance of social forces resulting in psychological dependence is the key to the social model. Socioeconomic status, ethnicity, subcultural mores, and elements of family interaction are crucial elements in understanding special needs of raciaUethnic minority populations who abuse alcohol and other drugs. The social model

