stresses the social nature of substance abusing behaviors that are influenced by peers and family members and helps to explain the success of social support groups like Alcoholics Anonymous.
Bacon, elaborating on Jellinek’s model, expanded the identified stages of alcoholism progression to include symptoms of escalating social and emotional problems in his interpersonal approach. l o He also emphasizes loss of control, but describes it as a turning point in time. Progressively severe social symptoms are accompanied by feelings of isolation and low selfworth.
Similar to the interpersonal approach is Martha Rogers’ interactive model in which individuals and their environments are seen as irreducible, four-dimensional energy fields interacting with one another in a continuously creative evolution.’ Family, groups and community are all parts of the environmental field and can be examined by focusing on the interpersonal interactions of the individual with that field.
Alcoholics Anonymous recognizes the progressive loss of control described by Jellinek and Bacon. Personal stories are filled with reports of broken marriages, lost jobs, lying, drunk driving arrests, accidents, and blackouts. The downward spiral involves not only a loss of control, but loss of family, friends, employment, health, and self-worth.

Responses
African American According to McNeil, l 3 close scrutiny of models and theories of addictions to alcohol and other drugs indicate that they are seemingly patterned after a white, middle-class ideology and value system. This can be expected when models or theories have been tested on only one population or racial group.
The disease, or medical model developed by Jellinek, was tested in the early 1950s on 98 male members of Alcoholics Anonymous (AA) followed by a sample of 2000 hospital patients. l 4 This theory is limited in its application to African-Americans since they were not aware of nor attending AA in the 1950s and were not likely to be in the hospitals as patients when the sample was drawn. In addition, Bell’’ maintains that the medical model is not applicable to African-Americans because it does not allow for acknowledgment of issues related to cultural differences.
The behavior modification model of addiction addresses the problem as one of learned behavior. Af-

