rican-Americans cope daily with discrimination, lack of opportunities, and poverty which cause some to use alcohol and other drugs. However, this model does not explain other influences which contribute to addiction in this population. For example, Allen found in her study of African-American women that
’‘’ social reasons were the biggest cause for using sub-
stances. Therefore, the model as a, single explanation of substance abuse in this population cannot be accepted.
The psychological model focuses on problems within the person. This negates other major influences and seems to contribute to a sense of confusion and insecurity following addictions treatment. African-Americans tend to need more concrete references and guidance as opposed to the abstract which frequently results from treatment based on this model.
The social model promotes the idea that attitudes, values, and drinking patterns of a given culture contribute to their rate of addiction. Elell’’ states that substance abuse among African-Americans is largely determined by how clear-cut the cultural rules are regarding alcohol and drug use. Some of the fastest growing rates of addiction are among people who experience cultural dislocation and technological advances along with breakdrown of the family. It seems that the social model is most relevant to addictions among African-Americans, but it, too, cannot stand alone.
Conceptual frameworks, models. and theories of addiction need to include all variables which have a significant influence on the rate of substance abuse in the African-American community. These variables include social, psychological, physical, economic, and political aspects.
Iranians There are few, if any, studies on addiction effects and outcomes among Iranians. Alcohol is the most common drug used by this cultural group, followed by opium. In order to establish which model of addiction is most effective, it is important to understand and examine some of the road blocks. First are religious beliefs. Drinking is considered a sin, and anyone who drinks needs to be punished according to Islamic law. Alcoholics, therefore, will not ask for help and their families are too ashamed to admit that there arle any problems. The cycle of addiction and destruction continues.
Currently in Iran, there are no liquor stores or bars, but people continue to drink by making their own alcohol at home. Physicians are fearful of diagnosing patients as alcoholic and treat only the symp-

64
toms of late stages of the disease. There are no treatment centers and Alcoholics Anonymous (AA) is nonexistent. Alcoholics and addicts don’t have the opportunity to receive help and remain closeted.
Opium continues to be widely abused, especially by the older population. There are still physicians who write prescriptions for opium to elderly patients for arthritic pain and discomfort.
An important factor to Iranians in the United States is their lack of insurance coverage. Most are middle-aged persons who left Iran after the new government was installed, and who came here to start a new life. Some are cared for by younger children who went to college and now are working, but who cannot carry their parents on their insurance coverage. Private insurance is too expensive and they cannot afford it. Others own small businesses, but are unable to buy health insurance. They have no coverage and treatment is not available to them.
The treatment model which would be most effective for Iranians is the medical model. It would be less threatening than the psychological, behavioral , or social models.
Native American The laws and legal aspects of drinking and purchase of liquor have always performed Native American cultures. Although some Indian leaders are so opposed to alcoholism that they advocate complete abstinence, bootlegging problems are increasing on all reservations. The question or assumption that Native Americans are more susceptible to the development of alcoholism is still unresolved.
Because drinking was illegal for so long, many Indians learned to consume available alcohol as soon as possible. The object of drinking was to get as drunk as possible as fast as one could. Because this opportunity was not always available, binge drinking became the norm. There would be long periods of sobriety with intervals of drunken stupor. Currently, among Natives of North America, drinking binges seem to occur in family groups and at the first of the month when checks arrive. Many families drink until the check is gone.
Alcoholism is the biggest health, psychosocial, legal, and economic problem among Native Americans today. Statistics vary, but most agree that alcoholism is of epidemic proportions and that every person and family is affected. The prevalence of related problems of violence, abuse, sexual abuse, suicide, FAS, and FAE are appallingly high.
There are many who favor the medical model of diagnosis for this cultural group. They think there is

