a physiological difference in Native Americans that makes them more susceptible to alcohol. The incidence of depression is very high, and some think treatment with antidepressants, benzodiazapines, and Prozac will decrease the need to self-medicate.
The behavioral model, especially used in the development of new and more effective coping skills, has been tried in some treatment situations. It generally is felt that the Indian person has poor coping skills and could develop more effective ones. It is difficult, however, to develop different coping skills with meager resources and lack of support systems. The use of aversion therapy and other behavior managements to control alcohol intake has not proven effective with Native Americans. The use of Antabuse is quite common and effective in some cases.
The psychological model is often incorporated with the social model in dealing with Native Americans. Indian drinkers have many subconscious conflicts; they are often immature and perceive themselves as inadequate in social and personal areas. Self-esteem is a major factor, in that many feel rejected, and unwanted and lack power in many aspects of their lives. Some Indians claim they drink in order to die.
The social model which involves family, tribe, and community seems to be the most widely accepted model for this group. Whole communities can serve as enablers because of the acceptance of alcoholism and related behavior. No family escapes the problems and dysfunctions associated with the disease. Family genograms indicate alcoholism is transgenerational and reveal a whole constellation of dysfunctions which support the concept of adult children of alcoholics as a distinct group.
Treatment approaches vary. Alcoholics Anonymous seems to be one answer. Some twelve-step programs are incorporating Native American beliefs and develop “the Red Road” philosophy. Many counselors encourage recovering alcoholics to search out spirituality from Native American ceremonies and practices. Sweat Lodges, Vision Quests, and Sun Dances seem to help some alcoholics and their families.
Hispanic Research findings from alcohol and other drug use in the Hispanic community are limited because of various methodological flaws. Therefore, there is less reliable information about alcohol and drug use among Hispanics than among non-Hispanic whites and non-Hispanic African Americans. The following problems have contributed to the lack of data: ( 1 ) absence of Hispanic identifiers in large na-

