tional surveys-this deficiency is currently being addressed; however it does not allow for any analysis of historical trends. An additional concern is the inconsistent use of identifiers for the major Hispanic subpopulations (e.g., Mexican Americans, Puerto Ricans, Cubans, and Central Americans). These subgroups exhibit marked sociodemographic differences and appear to have distinct characteristics with respect to alcohol and other drugs. (2) Undersampling of Hispanics; the characteristic differences within the Hispanic subgroups can be identified only with a sample size adequate enough to allow for independent analysis of data for each group and for stratification within groups by variables such as age, socioeconomic status, gender, and acculturation. (3) Inconsistent definitions; variations in definitions of abstinence, moderate use, and heavy drinking may lead to flawed results. l7 (4) Inadequate distinctions between variables; study results may be erroneously attributed to characteristics of ethnicity when in fact they may be more related to socioeconomic or educational status. ( 5 ) Lack of relevant data; with the exception of alcohol, virtually no literature exists on the attitudes of Hispanics toward substance use and abuse.
These issues make it difficult to explore different models of addiction. The behavioral model may not be entirely appropriate since very little is known of family-associated behaviors that shape the Hispanic individual’s attitudes and practices. The social model may be promising if one examines drinking and drugs in terms of cultural and social influence on lifestyle.

Conclusions
Models of addiction are tools for organizing and understanding substance abuse in the individual and family. Regardless of the particular model of addiction used to interpret or describe alcohol or other drug abusing behaviors, traditional values and rituals associated with various cultural groups need to be learned, respected, and considered in plans for individualized care.

